    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="216"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d216">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">310.265/1–1551</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of State</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d216fn1">Drafted by the Director of the Office of Western
                        European Affairs (Byington). Initialed for the Secretary of State by Francis
                        E. Meloy, Jr., of the Executive Secretariat.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-15">January 15,
                            1951</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Admission of Italy into the United Nations</p>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#top #nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>Ambassador Tarchiani, Italian Embassy</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>The Secretary of State</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Homer M. Byington, Jr., <gloss target="#t_WE1">WE</gloss>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Ambassador Tarchiani said that one impression he had received very strongly
                    during his visit to Italy was the concern of public opinion that Italy was
                    tending to be pushed on the sidelines when main issues were discussed. He felt
                    that the Italian people were very much aware of Italy’s failure to obtain
                    admission into the United Nations and that there was some impression that
                    Italy’s allies had not supported her strongly enough in that connection. He said
                    that if Communist China were to be admitted into the <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                        >UN</gloss> and Italy not, the resultant reaction on Italian public opinion
                    would be most unfavorable.<note n="2" xml:id="d216fn2">For documentation
                        regarding the question of Chinese representation, see <ref target="#pg_209"
                            >pp. 209</ref> ff.</note> I said that as he knew, we were strongly in
                    favor of Italian admission into the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>.</p>
            </div>
